<p>By <em>ending</em> the evening with a clean <em>slate</em>, we can avoid getting <em>buried</em> in <em>overdue</em> tasks and <em>tackle</em> tomorrow with <em>renewed</em> energy.</p>

<h2 id="reflect-regularly">Reflect regularly</h2>

<p>Youâ€™ve made planning your day a habit, <em>translated</em> your long-term goals into <em>actionable</em> tasks, <em>chosen</em> a productivity method, and <em>selected</em> your tool of choice. Youâ€™re set for more productive days that build to more meaningful weeks, months, and years.</p>

<p>However, donâ€™t let your process run on <em>autopilot</em>. Take some time to regularly consider <em>whether</em> your approach to daily planning is <em>helping</em> you accomplish more. Make time every so often, perhaps during a <a href="https://blog.doist.com/weekly-review/">weekly review</a>, to consider <em>whether</em> your planning process is working or could be <em>tweaked</em> or even <em>overhauled</em> to be more effective.</p>

<p>Consider these questions:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Are my days calm and intentional or <em>stressful</em> and <em>haphazard</em>?</li>
  <li>Did I complete all my daily planning sessions or skip some?</li>
  <li>Do I feel <em>accomplished</em> at the end of most days?</li>
  <li>Are my high priority days being <em>addressed</em>?</li>
  <li>Am I on track to meet my long-term goals?</li>
  <li>This day was <em>especially</em> productive â€” why?</li>
  <li>I <em>accomplished</em> nothing <em>impactful</em> on this day â€” why?</li>
</ul>

<p>In being honest about how our days went and how weâ€™re faring on our big goals, we can fine-tune our daily planning for better results. <em>Hectic</em> days might mean we need to <em>prioritize</em> more effectively or find a way to <em>delegate</em> work. Missing daily planning sessions might mean theyâ€™re too long and could benefit from a more <em>streamlined</em> approach. If weâ€™re not <em>moving</em> towards our goals, it may mean we have too many or weâ€™re not adding them to our days with enough frequency or intention. We might simply like pen and paper while weâ€™ve <em>forced</em> ourselves to try a <em>shiny</em> new app. Whatever the issue, work to resolve it by modifying your daily planning process.</p>

<p>Itâ€™s not <em>uncommon</em> to need to experiment and try a few <em>iterations</em> of daily planning before we land on the method that actually lead to getting more <em>done</em>.</p>

